I agree about housing is a fundamental human right, but it's crucial to keep in mind that the subject is actually more complex than that. According to the UN expert on adequate housing, Leilani Farha, houseing has increasingly turned into lucrative business (upside to the market index or stock) rather than a fundamental necessity. Because it illustrates the potential negative effeccts of treating housiing solely as a commercial venture, this perspective is crucial.

Some, however, might argue that treating housing as an investment can nalso have positive effects. Private investment, for instance, may enhance infrastructure, build better housing, and stimulate the economy. New ideas and effective building methods are frequently introduced by developers, which may enhance the quality of housing and generate employment in the construction industry and related industries.

Additionally, the essay highlights the drawbacks of commodiying housing but fails to take into account that governments can legislate to strike a balance between profit and social benefit. Tax breas for developers who create inexpensive houses are one example of a policy that may benefit both investors and the community.

Last but not least, if housingg is seen as exclusively a human right, the market forces that contribute to the advancement and development of housing may be restricted. Seeingg housing as both a right and an economic asset might result in more sustainable and equitable solutions, where individuals have stable housing without sacrificing access to development and innovation.

In summary, it is imperative to recognize housing as a human right, but we must also comprehend the nuances of the housing market and how it operates. Good regulation can improve the system for everybody because we human drive the value in the market.
